# Action beyond the ballot: We must rethink, retool Nairobi for the future

While devolution corrected decades of overcentralization elsewhere and brought power closer to the people across Kenya’s 46 counties, Nairobi has remained politically volatile and stubborn altogether. Every five years since the rollout of the devolution dispensation in March 2013, Nairobi has perpetually experienced tumultuous transitions in its leadership. As such, service delivery and long-term planning have long been in limbo, and Kenya, more often than not, bears the brunt of these storms.

## A Capital Unlike Any Other

By any measure, Nairobi is no ordinary county. It is the socio-economic and political capital of Kenya, the innovation centre of East Africa, and the only city in the Global South that hosts two major United Nations agencies; United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) and UN-Habitat. Yet, Nairobi is still administered like other counties whose governance scope is comparatively local. Thus, the city's chronic dysfunction is bred and fed by this contradiction.

## When Nairobi Falters, Kenya Suffers

As it is, Nairobi does not serve Nairobians or Kenyans alone. Its infrastructure carries both international and national significance. When waste management fails in Nairobi, it becomes a terrible diplomatic faux pas. Traffic collapse slows the economy countrywide, rising insecurity smirches Kenya’s global image. When Nairobi catches a cold, the whole country sneezes.

## Global Precedents

Across the world, capitals are governed distinctly for good reason. Washington D.C. operates under federal authority. Canberra is constituted as a federal territory. Closer home, Abuja is directly overseen by Nigeria’s federal government. The principle here is simple: a capital city is an inviolable national asset.

Every election, the question of Nairobi’s metropolitan future flares up. Citizens and some leaders, fed up with poor sanitation, sprawling informal settlements and fragmented planning, voice their frustrations—but the debate fizzles out, and the city ends up in the same familiar mess, bigger and more tangled.

## A Case for Metropolitan Status

For posterity, Nairobi ought to be restructured into a metropolitan territory—a "mother town" administered by the national government through a professional metropolitan authority insulated from local political turbulence, manipulative syndicates, and rogue cartels.

Besides accounting for a disproportionate share of Kenya’s tax revenue, the city also acts as a symbol of national unity where people from all backgrounds gather in shared identity. Protecting its functionality and sanity is not a local issue but an exponential expression of macroeconomic policy.

## Learning from the NMS Era

We already witnessed partial national takeover during the Nairobi Metropolitan Services (NMS) era—proof that the national government inevitably intervenes when the capital deteriorates. Why not formalize what reality already demands?

A metropolitan authority run under national oversight would enable long-term infrastructural and economic planning beyond electoral cycles. It would harmonize transport, urban planning, orderliness, and land policy across Nairobi. Additionally, it would integrate policing, transport regulation, and environmental management under a unified structure. Further, the authority would efficiently streamline coordination between national security organs and urban administration as cogs of the same wheel.

## Constitutional Reform Is Not Sacrilege

Yes, transforming Nairobi into a nationally administered metropolis would require constitutional amendment. But even so, constitutional reform is not sacrilege. The constitution is a living document designed to respond to evolving realities. If Nairobi’s scale, complexity, and strategic importance exceed normal county capacity, reform would not be betrayal but maturity.

Responding to Nairobi’s uniqueness would not undermine devolution or diminish other counties in any way. It would embody realistic governance needs, and the ultimate value exceeds the cost.

## A City That Matches Its Status

The debate is neither about disenfranchisement nor stripping Nairobians of representation. It is about creating a governance model that matches Nairobi’s prominence at the national and international scale—a functional, efficient, technocratic, and accountable city shielded from narrow political theatrics and parochial mentalities.

Nairobi is Kenya’s diplomatic hub, economic engine, and face to the world. If we truly recognize its strategic importance and appreciate the metropolis it has become, then we must be bold enough to design a system that reflects that reality.

